||===========================================================||
|| My STM32 NUCLEO-G071RB (ARM Cortex-M0+) Learning progress ||
||===========================================================||

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

REQUIREMENTS
============

* arm-none-eabi-gcc (Compiler)
* make (Build System)
* openOCD
* GDB (for ARM processors, I used `gdb-multiarch`)

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

BUILDING AND UPLOADING
======================

To Build, go into one of the folders and run
```
make
```

To build as well as flash(upload) the program after that, then run
```
make flash
```

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ORGANIZATION
============

Organization of the folders are in such a way that each folder is self-complete,
and no need for extra things other than the requirements mentioned above. List
of the folders with their brief description:

01. LED BLINK: Made a LED Blink, enable clock for GPIOA, then set the MODE of
    Pin5 of GPIOA to output-mode, and then setting and clearing the
    corresponding bit in the OUTPUT Register of GPIOA after some delay.

02. PUSH BUTTON POLLING: GPIO Input, Read the user button, debounce in software,
    toggle LED on press. Understand pull-up/down config.

03. SYSTICK TIMER DELAY: Replace the crude loop delay with SysTick-based
    millisecond delay.

04. GENERAL PURPOSE TIMER DELAY: Used TIM2 in basic upcounting mode to generate
    accurate time delays. Understand PSC and ARR registers. 

05. BUTTON-CONTROLLED BLINK RATE: Each button press increases the LED toggle
    speed through preset intervals, cycling through them. We used non-blocking
    patterns.
    
06. PWM OUTPUT: Used the TIM2 Channel, configure TIM2 in PWM mode on the LED
    pin. Manually control duty cycle to dim/brighten the LED.

07. BREATHING LED: (PWM + SysTick) Smoothly ramp duty cycle up and down using a
    sine or linear sweep, creating a breathing effect.

08. EXTI - EXTERNAL INTERRUPT ON BUTTON: Wire the user button to EXTI line. On
    interrupt, toggle a flag. Understand NVIC, priority, and pending flags.

09. EXTI TOGGLE - LED BLINK VS PWM MODE: Each button press (via EXTI) switches
    the LED between free-running blink mode and PWM breathing mode.